these reactions were used as flux monitor, in order to
supplement the flux measurement by a faraday cup.
The target element barium was irradiated in form of a
Ba-glass obtained from Schott Glaswerke GMBH, Mainz.
It  contained 40.13% Barium.  Barium was the only heavy
element  in  this  glass,  and  all  impurities   which
possibly could interfere with the production of La, Ba,
Cs and Xe isotopes during p-irradiation were  found  to
be negligible.
The Ba-glass was purchased as a plate, from which rods
of 15.7 mm Diameter were drilled by a hollow drill. The
rods were sawed into discs, each having a thickness of
0.1 mm to 0.2 mm and polished with a diamond grinding
wheel. The cleaned glass-slices were degassed for 1
hour at 250 Celsius degree and 10(-6) torr.
